t’s work to the humanities and social sciences. In a new preface, Scott reflects on the book’s legacy and implications for contemporary politics as well as what she has reconsidered as a result of her engagement with psychoanalytic theory. The book also includes a previously unpublished essay, “The Conundrum of Equality,” which takes up the question of affirmative action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aSex rolexHistory. 0aWomenxEmploymentzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking class womenxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2018z978311070863908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/scot1880040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231547611423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231547611/original  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-070863-9  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles